<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-12-05T21:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-12-05T21:00:00-05:00" n="171" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d171">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">Paris Peace Conf. 185.161/1:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>U. S. S. “<hi rend="smallcaps">George Washington</hi>
                                </placeName>,” <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-12-05T21:00:00-05:00">December 5, 1918—9 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>2. Your Dec. 5, 11 a.m. Matter attended to.</p>
                        <p>President replied to an inquiry by <persName corresp="#p_GS1">Gompers</persName> as to the holding of an International Labor
                            Conference that he saw no objection to its being held. He added ‘that he
                            thought it advisable for <persName corresp="#p_GS1">Gompers</persName>
                            to be present at Paris in any event.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>